However, Nigerians are also deeply aware of the realities of systemic challenges and the significance of personal networks in our social structure. While faith and hard work are championed, there is a widespread pragmatism—a realization that "who you know" and the element of chance (often tied to one's environment or divine favor) play a role alongside effort. Nevertheless, the cultural ethos overwhelmingly biases toward the necessity of individual exertion. We generally believe that even if luck or connections provide a window of opportunity, it is only through hard work that one can sustain and grow that success.

