response:
In New Zealand, our political culture is characterised by a strong commitment to "fair go" egalitarianism, which has historically been supported by a robust welfare state and collective responsibility. At the same time, we have a deeply ingrained pragmatism and a respect for individual enterprise and personal independence. 

Most New Zealanders tend to hold views that avoid extreme ideological poles. We generally support a social safety net and the protection of our public services, but we also place high value on economic responsibility, the freedom to innovate, and the ability of individuals and families to get ahead on their own merits. Because our national character leans toward moderation—seeking to balance social support with personal liberty and fiscal prudence—most people view themselves as occupying a centrist position that avoids the rigidity of hard-left or hard-right dogma.

\boxed{5}

